recordings.loc: Arcata, Humboldt County, California
recordings.type: song, quavered song and ank, scold
recordings.rmk:
This 6+ minute recording documents two vocalizing Wrentits. The primary vocalist was a scolding Wrentit assumed to be an adult of undetermined sex. This bird was consorting with another Wrentit of undetermined age and sex. Given a description of young Wrentit vocalizations in the Bird of North American account this second bird may have been a young of the year.

The scold notes may be heard throughout the recording but the best signals are in the first third of the recording.

The vocalizations of the second bird may be more interesting. In the beginning of this recording the second bird was definitely seen and heard giving a short “ank” (maybe “peep") several times. It definitely also gave a quavered (called yodelly in my original description—let’s chalk that up to artistic license, shall we) series of notes that may be undeveloped song. Toward the end of the recording there are signals on the spectrogram and were not perceived in the field. These might be from the Wrentit as well as they have a similar signature.

The “ank” may be heard at 0:19 (19.810), 0:41 (41.975), 0:47 (47.689), and 2:03 (2:03.334). Bird of North America account possibly describes this call thus: Grinnell (1913) described a peep and a low chuck, both given singly and faintly, perhaps serving as contact calls when moving through dense understory together. Recently fledged young (at least as young as 12 d) sometimes peep, wheat, or tu-wheat repeatedly, perhaps begging to adults approaching with food.

Two instances of the quavered note can be heard at 4:01 (4:01.514) and 6:08.5 (6:09.272). Bird of North America account say this: Juveniles as young as 10 d have been heard attempting weak songs, similar to those of adult females. Appears to function as contact signal; young separated from family flock “sing” more frequently and cease upon arrival of adult. In early summer, unformed male songs may be heard with no introductory notes. One male in a group of 3 gave a shaky trill, sounding as if he could not stay on pitch. The other 2 males eventually joined in, all sounding jumbled (J. Thomas pers. comm.). Further study needed.

Possible vocs: 5:33 (5:33.936), 5:34.5 (5:35.123) and 5:37 (5:37.651).

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S24203706>

This recording was made with an iPhone 4s with Sennheiser microphone and Røde Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of these birds' utterances.
